// Auto-generated from Learning_Material_-_Product_Navigator.pdf
// All 5 archetypes x 20 topics = 100 content entries

export type Archetype = 'strategist' | 'explorer' | 'operator' | 'advocate' | 'builder'

export type TopicKey = 'productSense' | 'guesstimates' | 'prioritisation' | 'productStrategy' | 'competitiveAnalysis' | 'metricsKpis' | 'abTesting' | 'goToMarket' | 'roadmapping' | 'stakeholderManagement' | 'techFundamentals' | 'aiMlForPms' | 'dataSql' | 'systemDesign' | 'userResearch' | 'uxThinking' | 'customerEmpathy' | 'writtenCommunication' | 'productStorytelling' | 'stakeholderInfluence'

export const contentLibrary: Record<Archetype, Record<string, string>> = {
  strategist: {
    productSense: `"Product sense is noticing what everyone else walks past." WHAT THIS IS Product sense is the ability to look at a product and know, without being told, what is right and what is off. It is taste applied to products. The PM who walks into an app, navigates two screens, and immediately identifies the problem is not guessing — they have built a calibrated model of users through deliberate observation. Think of a tailor with 30 years of experience. They can look at a person and immediately know what cut will suit them, without asking. Pattern recognition built through sustained attention.`,
    guesstimates: `"You do not need the exact answer. You need a good enough answer fast enough to make a decision." THE BIG IDEA Imagine you run a small lemonade stand outside your house. You need one pitcher, one table, and a few cups. Life is simple. Now imagine your lemonade goes viral on Instagram. Suddenly 100,000 people are walking toward your front door at the same time. Your folding table would collapse. Your one pitcher would run dry in seconds. You would have a disaster, not a business.`,
    prioritisation: `"Every yes is a hundred nos. Make the nos on purpose." WHAT THIS IS Prioritisation is the art of deciding what not to build. Anyone can generate a list of good ideas. The PM's job is to decide which three of those forty good ideas the team works on — and defend that decision when the CEO's favourite idea is not on the list. Think of it like having ₹100 and five friends each asking for money. You cannot give everyone everything. You decide who needs it most, who will use it best, and what produces the most good for the whole group. Prioritisation is that decision made systematically.`,
    productStrategy: `"Strategy is not what you will do. It is what you will not do." WHAT THIS IS Strategy is the answer to one question: given everything we could do, what will we focus on — and what will we deliberately ignore? A team without strategy builds the thing in front of them. A team with strategy builds the thing that moves toward a defined destination and says no to everything that does not serve that destination. Think of a general leading an army to a mountain. Many paths exist. The general's job is not to take all of them simultaneously.`,
    competitiveAnalysis: `"Do not just map what competitors do. Map where they choose not to compete." WHAT THIS IS Competitive analysis is understanding who else is solving the same problem, how, and for whom — and where the structural gaps are. The most common version is a feature comparison matrix. The more valuable question is: where are all the players choosing not to compete, and why? KEY FRAMEWORK Feature Matrix with Strategic Tags: Layer 1 maps each competitor's capabilities against user needs and finds the gaps.`,
    metricsKpis: `"Numbers without context are just noise. Numbers with context are a superpower." THE BIG IDEA Imagine you are a doctor. When a patient comes in, you do not just look at them and say 'you look fine.' You check real signals — pulse, temperature, blood pressure. You look for what is actually happening inside, not just what the surface looks like. A product manager uses metrics the same way. Metrics are the product's vital signs. They tell you what is actually happening — not what you hope is happening or what your boss thinks is happening.`,
    abTesting: `"The only way to know if something works is to test it on real people doing real things." THE BIG IDEA Imagine a farmer who wants to know which fertiliser makes corn grow taller. He could try one fertiliser this year and a different one next year. But then the rain might be different, the temperature might be different, the seeds might be different. He would never know if it was the fertiliser that made the difference or just the weather. So instead, he splits his field in half. Same soil. Same sun. Same seeds. Fertiliser A on the left side. Fertiliser B on the right side.`,
    goToMarket: `"A great product with the wrong GTM is a tree falling in an empty forest." WHAT THIS IS Go-to-Market is the plan for how your product reaches the people it is meant for. GTM failure is almost always a mismatch problem: the way you are trying to sell the product does not match what you are selling. You cannot sell a product that requires a 45-minute sales call through a Facebook ad.`,
    roadmapping: `"A roadmap is not a promise. It is a statement of priorities." WHAT THIS IS A roadmap connects what you are doing today to what you are trying to become. It is a communication tool as much as a planning tool. Its most underappreciated function: it is a political shield. Once your roadmap has been agreed on, a PM can decline ad-hoc requests by pointing to the document. The no is structural, not personal.`,
    stakeholderManagement: `"You are not the boss of anyone. You are the person everyone should want to work with." WHAT THIS IS PMs have enormous responsibility and almost no direct authority. Everything is accomplished through influence, alignment, and trust. The most common failure: PMs who walk into stakeholder conversations with the answer already decided, and use the conversation to sell rather than to listen. KEY FRAMEWORK Spiral Dynamics for Communication: Order-focused people (engineering managers, compliance) need structure and process first. Success-focused people (sales, growth) need the ROI and the metric.`,
    techFundamentals: `"You do not need to write code. You need to understand what the code is doing — and why it matters for the product." THE BIG IDEA — THE ARIA PATTERN Every technical concept in the curriculum is taught using the ARIA pattern: Analogy first, Real-life example, Intuition builder, then the Actual explanation. This is the order in this section too. When you encounter a technical idea you do not understand, the fastest path to understanding is always the analogy. Start there, then build up to the actual explanation.`,
    aiMlForPms: `"AI is not magic. It is a very fast, very well-read student who sometimes makes things up with total confidence." THE BIG IDEA Most people think of AI as something magical — a brain that knows everything. It is not. It is closer to the world's most well-read student who has memorised billions of sentences and learned the statistical pattern of which words tend to follow which other words. When you ask it a question, it does not look up the answer the way you would search a database. It predicts what the most likely next words are, based on everything it has read. Most of the time, this produces something accurate.`,
    dataSql: `"Data tells you what happened. Judgment tells you what to do about it." WHAT THIS IS Data and SQL is the ability to work with numbers and databases well enough to ask real questions and get real answers — without always relying on an analyst. You need to be fluent enough to know what question to ask, verify whether the answer used the right data, and spot when an analysis is measuring the wrong thing.`,
    systemDesign: `"A PM who understands system design does not just approve the architecture. They shape the product constraints that make architecture decisions meaningful." WHAT THIS IS System design is the craft of identifying bottlenecks before users do. Architecture decisions made in year one constrain product decisions in year three. A PM who understands system design protects future product optionality. A PM who does not becomes a prisoner of their own architecture.`,
    userResearch: `"Your job is not to validate what you already believe. Your job is to be surprised." WHAT THIS IS User research is the practice of understanding people before you build things for them. The most important rule: ask about what people have done, not what they will do. People are terrible at predicting their own future behaviour. KEY FRAMEWORK Structured Discovery: (1) List your assumptions — these are your biases, test them not confirm them.`,
    uxThinking: `"Great design is invisible. Bad design is all you can see." WHAT THIS IS UX — User Experience — is everything a person feels while using your product. Macro-interactions are the big actions. Micro-interactions are the small moments in between. Individually trivial. Collectively, they determine whether a product feels premium or mediocre.`,
    customerEmpathy: `"Empathy is not feeling bad for someone. It is understanding their world well enough to act on their behalf." WHAT THIS IS There is a difference between sympathy and empathy. Sympathy: 'that must be hard.' Empathy: understanding their situation so well that you can anticipate what they need before they say it. For a PM: you know your users' world well enough to make decisions on their behalf when they are not in the room. KEY FRAMEWORK Empathy Mapping: four quadrants. Says (verbatim words — not paraphrased). Thinks (beliefs and assumptions — often contradicts what they say).`,
    writtenCommunication: `"A PM who writes well, thinks well. The document is the proof." WHAT THIS IS In product management, everything consequential happens through documents. Your documents are your most visible work — what people share when you are not in the room. The most important shift: think of a document not as a final answer but as a thinking tool. You write to figure things out — then share it to get the holes in your thinking identified before you build the wrong thing.`,
    productStorytelling: `"A strategy that cannot be told is a strategy that cannot be executed." THE BIG IDEA Think about how milk gets to your house. Amul does not ship every bottle directly from one factory in Gujarat to every home in India. That would be impossibly slow and expensive. Instead, they built a distribution network — local distributors, corner stores, neighbourhood shops — so the milk is already nearby when you need it. Storytelling for a PM is the same idea. You cannot pitch your ideas to every person individually every time you need something to happen.`,
    stakeholderInfluence: `"Do not blame the person. Fix the system they are operating in." WHAT THIS IS Influence is not persuasion. Persuasion is convincing someone to do what you want. Influence is building an environment where the right thing to do becomes the obvious thing to do. The key shift: stop thinking about people as obstacles and start thinking about the systems they are embedded in. When a sales team keeps requesting one-off product changes, blaming the sales team solves nothing.`,
  },
  explorer: {
    productSense: `"Product sense is noticing what everyone else walks past."  The gap is that these opinions are not yet grounded in a framework. When an interviewer asks 'why is that a bad UX?' the Explorer answer is 'it just feels off.' The PM answer names the layer of the iceberg that is broken, the principle being violated, and the user behaviour being harmed. Instinct is the starting point. Structured instinct is the skill.`,
    guesstimates: `"You do not need the exact answer. You need a good enough answer fast enough to make a decision."  The gap is the structured decomposition that makes estimates defensible under pressure. Explorer estimates often start from the top (total market size) without building from the bottom (unit-level assumptions). Interviewers probe the assumptions, not the headline number. The framework is what survives the probe.`,
    prioritisation: `"Every yes is a hundred nos. Make the nos on purpose."  This produces a backlog that reflects the most recent input rather than the most important problem. The PM skill is building a system that makes prioritisation decisions defensible to a room full of stakeholders with different incentives — not just a reflection of your current conviction. THE BIG IDEA Prioritisation is the art of deciding what not to build.`,
    productStrategy: `"Strategy is not what you will do. It is what you will not do."  The gap is translating that strategic thinking into product strategy specifically: the discipline of decomposing a long-term vision into a hierarchy of bets, themes, and sprint tasks with clear ownership and measurable outcomes. Founder strategy and PM strategy look similar from the outside. The difference is the precision of the hierarchy and the accountability at each level.`,
    competitiveAnalysis: `"Do not just map what competitors do. Map where they choose not to compete."  The gap is structural analysis: not just knowing what competitors are doing but understanding the bets they are placing, the users they are implicitly ignoring, and where the market will be contested next. Competitive intelligence is not the same as competitive analysis. THE BIG IDEA The most common competitive analysis is a feature comparison matrix.`,
    metricsKpis: `"Numbers without context are just noise. Numbers with context are a superpower."  The gap is product metrics specifically: the leading indicators that predict business health before outcomes appear, the user behaviour events that tell you what is actually happening inside the product, and the north star metric that unifies the team around a single measure of value delivered. Business metrics and product metrics are related but not the same.`,
    abTesting: `"The only way to know if something works is to test it on real people doing real things."  The gap is the rigour underneath: statistical significance, the 14-day minimum, the guardrail metrics named before the test launches, the single variable rule. Explorer experiments often change multiple things at once (which makes results uninterpretable) and are called early (which produces noise, not signal). The mechanics of a valid test are learnable and non-negotiable.`,
    goToMarket: `"A great product with the wrong GTM is a tree falling in an empty forest."  They understand GTM intuitively. The gap is the structural alignment test: does the channel match the product complexity, does the revenue model match how users experience value, does the sales motion match the buyer's decision process? Explorer GTMs often work by hustle and relationship in the early stage but do not scale because the channel-model-product alignment was never made explicit.`,
    roadmapping: `"A roadmap is not a promise. It is a statement of priorities."  The gap is the strategic layer underneath: connecting each item to a mission, which connects to a vision, which makes every decision traceable and every no defensible. Explorer roadmaps are often opportunistic — reflecting the latest conversation, the most urgent request, or the most exciting idea. PM roadmaps are strategic contracts. THE BIG IDEA A roadmap connects what you are doing today to what you are trying to become.`,
    stakeholderManagement: `"You are not the boss of anyone. You are the person everyone should want to work with." WHAT THIS IS PMs have enormous responsibility and almost no direct authority. Everything is done through influence, alignment, and trust. Stakeholder management is the practice of building those things deliberately. The most common failure: PMs who walk into stakeholder conversations with the answer already decided and use the conversation to sell rather than to listen. KEY FRAMEWORK — SPIRAL DYNAMICS The same message lands differently depending on who you are talking to.`,
    techFundamentals: `"You do not need to write code. You need to understand what the code is doing and why it matters." WHAT THIS IS Tech fundamentals for PMs: the internet cascade (DNS → TLS → HTTP → CDN → database — all in 200ms), frontend vs. backend (dining room vs. kitchen), APIs as contracts between systems (REST for fixed menus, GraphQL for build-your-own), databases (SQL for consistency-critical data, NoSQL for speed), and stateless architecture (no single server stores session state, enabling horizontal scaling).`,
    aiMlForPms: `"AI is not a feature. It is a capability layer that changes what problems you can solve."  The gap is the mechanics underneath: what LLMs actually are, why they fail the way they do, and what product design decisions follow from those failure modes. Using AI fluently is not the same as understanding AI well enough to build products on top of it. THE BIG IDEA Large Language Models are probabilistic next-token prediction engines.`,
    dataSql: `"Data tells you what happened. Judgment tells you what to do about it."  The gap is product analytics specifically: event-level data that captures user behaviour inside the product, the SQL fluency to query it directly, and the judgment to ask the right question before running the query. Explorer data work is often downstream of what analysts produce. PM data work begins upstream: defining what gets tracked and why.`,
    systemDesign: `"System design is the craft of identifying bottlenecks before users do."  The gap is the vocabulary and framework to have a precise conversation about trade-offs: CAP theorem, caching strategies, consistency models, and the product decisions that follow from each. Intuition about scale is not the same as a mental model of system design.`,
    userResearch: `"Your job is not to validate what you already believe. Your job is to be surprised."  The gap is structure: the conversations are real but the output is undisciplined. Explorer user research tends to confirm existing direction rather than challenge it, because the questions are shaped by current hypotheses rather than designed to surface unknown unknowns. Talking to users is not the same as doing user research.`,
    uxThinking: `"Great design is invisible. Bad design is all you can see."  The gap is the vocabulary and framework to make those opinions actionable in a product team. 'This feels off' is an Explorer response. 'The conceptual model does not match the user's mental model, which is causing confusion at the interaction design layer' is a PM response. The iceberg gives you the vocabulary. THE BIG IDEA UX is everything a person feels while using your product. The Heinz ketchup distinction: a glass bottle is good UI.`,
    customerEmpathy: `"Empathy is not feeling bad for someone. It is understanding their world well enough to act on their behalf."  The gap is systematic empathy: the ability to understand users you are not, in contexts you have not been in, for problems that may not match your own experience. Founder empathy is often empathy for yourself. PM empathy extends to users whose world is genuinely different from yours.`,
    writtenCommunication: `"A PM who writes well, thinks well. The document is the proof."  The gap is PM document discipline: writing that is a thinking tool first and a communication tool second. Explorer documents often start from a conclusion and work backward. PM documents start from the problem statement and work forward — including the holes in thinking that need to be fixed before building begins. THE BIG IDEA Almost everything consequential in product management happens through documents.`,
    productStorytelling: `"A strategy that cannot be told is a strategy that cannot be executed."  The gap is operational storytelling: the kind that happens weekly, not quarterly, that builds a compounding reputation through consistent visible thinking rather than one-off presentations. Explorer storytelling tends to be episodic and high-stakes. PM storytelling is systematic and distributed. THE BIG IDEA Storytelling for a PM is Distribution Leverage.`,
    stakeholderInfluence: `"Do not blame the person. Fix the system they are operating in." WHAT THIS IS Influence is not persuasion. It is building an environment where the right thing to do becomes the obvious thing to do. Stop thinking about people as obstacles and start thinking about the systems they are embedded in. When a sales team keeps requesting one-off product changes, the question is not how to stop them — it is what in the system makes those requests feel necessary and rational.`,
  },
  operator: {
    productSense: `"Product sense is noticing what everyone else walks past."  This is real and valuable. The product sense gap is at a different layer — noticing what the product should become, not just how it is currently running. The mistake is optimising delivery of a product that should have been redesigned. THE BIG IDEA Product sense is the ability to look at a product and know — without being told — what is right and what is off.`,
    guesstimates: `"You do not need the exact answer. You need a good enough answer fast enough to make a decision."  The guesstimate gap is not comfort with numbers; it is the ability to produce a defensible estimate from first principles when no dashboard exists and no analyst is available.`,
    prioritisation: `"Every yes is a hundred nos. Make the nos on purpose."  This is legitimate execution prioritisation. The PM gap is product prioritisation — deciding what should be built at all, not just in what order. The mistake is treating the backlog as a fixed input to be sequenced, rather than a hypothesis to be challenged. A PM owns the what and why. An Operator owns the when and how. The shift requires learning to make the first decision, not just the second.`,
    productStrategy: `"Strategy is not what you will do. It is what you will not do."  They translate strategic decisions into delivery plans, manage dependencies, and hold the team accountable to outcomes. The gap is upstream: forming the strategic direction in the first place. The mistake is assuming that strategy is set by someone else — a CEO, a CPO, a leadership team — and the PM's job is to receive it and execute. A product PM owns strategy at the product level.`,
    competitiveAnalysis: `"Do not just map what competitors do. Map where they choose not to compete."  This produces a good real-time awareness of what competitors are shipping. The gap is structural analysis — understanding why competitors are making the choices they are making, what bets they are placing, and where the market is going to be contested next. Feature tracking is tactical intelligence. Competitive analysis is strategic intelligence.`,
    metricsKpis: `"Numbers without context are just noise. Numbers with context are a superpower." WHAT THIS IS Metrics are the product's vital signs. The challenge is picking the right ones. A vanity metric sounds impressive but does not help you make a single better decision. Apply the So What Test: keep asking 'so what?' until the number points toward something you can act on. KEY FRAMEWORK — AARRR PIRATE METRICS • Acquisition: every path through which a new user finds the product. How many arrive, at what cost, of what quality? • Activation: the aha moment on day one.`,
    abTesting: `"The only way to know if something works is to test it on real people doing real things." WHAT THIS IS A/B testing splits users into two groups, measures which produces better results, and keeps the winner. The dangerous thing: results can look real when they are just noise. The p-value answers whether the result could have happened by chance (threshold: below 0.05). The 14-day rule: never call a test before 14 days — day-3 results are almost always noise from the novelty effect.`,
    goToMarket: `"A great product with the wrong GTM is a tree falling in an empty forest." WHAT THIS IS GTM is the complete system for how your product reaches the people it is meant for. GTM failure is almost always a mismatch: the way you are trying to sell the product does not match what you are selling. You cannot sell a product requiring a 45-minute onboarding call through a Facebook ad. You cannot sell a ₹50,000 enterprise subscription through a self-serve sign-up button.`,
    roadmapping: `"A roadmap is not a promise. It is a statement of priorities." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You have lived in roadmaps. You know the mechanics of maintaining one, communicating changes, managing stakeholder expectations around it, and using it as a delivery coordination tool. You probably know which roadmap formats work for which audiences and which stakeholder dynamics cause roadmaps to fail. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is upstream: being the person who sets the roadmap rather than the person who maintains it. Operators often inherit product direction and translate it into delivery plans.`,
    stakeholderManagement: `"You are not the boss of anyone. You are the person everyone should want to work with." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW Stakeholder management is your daily practice. You know how to align competing priorities, navigate difficult conversations, build trust across functions, and keep a project moving when people disagree. You have developed instincts for when to push, when to hold, and when to let something go in service of the larger goal. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in what you are managing stakeholders toward.`,
    techFundamentals: `"You do not need to write code. You need to understand what the code is doing and why it matters." WHAT THIS IS Tech fundamentals for PMs covers the invisible machinery of digital products: the internet cascade (DNS → TLS → HTTP → CDN → database) that happens in 200ms when a user searches; frontend vs. backend (dining room vs.`,
    aiMlForPms: `"AI is not a feature. It is a capability layer that changes what problems you can solve."  This is real value but it is only the first tier. The gap is understanding AI as a product capability and strategic bet: what does it make possible that was not possible before, what are its structural failure modes, and how does it change the competitive landscape of your market? AI fluency for a PM starts with the mechanics, not the productivit`,
    dataSql: `"Data tells you what happened. Judgment tells you what to do about it."  This is execution data. The PM gap is product data — what users are actually doing in the product, which behaviours predict retention, which flows break silently. Operators are often fluent with project management data but have not worked directly with product analytics data. The shift is from measuring delivery health to measuring product health.`,
    systemDesign: `"System design is the craft of identifying bottlenecks before users do." WHAT THIS IS System design is the architecture of how a product handles scale, failure, and growth.`,
    userResearch: `"Your job is not to validate what you already believe. Your job is to be surprised."  This produces real user signal. The gap is that it is all reactive: users who have problems, stakeholders who have complaints, teams who raise blockers. Proactive, structured discovery — going looking for problems before they escalate — is the PM skill. The mistake is treating the support queue as a substitute for intentional user research.`,
    uxThinking: `"Great design is invisible. Bad design is all you can see."  The gap is PM ownership of the user experience across that entire chain — not just ensuring fidelity to the spec, but ensuring the spec was right. The mistake is treating UX as a design team output rather than a PM responsibility. THE BIG IDEA UX is everything a person feels while using your product. Not just whether it works.`,
    customerEmpathy: `"Empathy is not feeling bad for someone. It is understanding their world well enough to act on their behalf."  This is real relational empathy and it is what makes Operators trusted. The gap is empathy for the end user — the person using the product who never attends a sprint review, never escalates through a stakeholder channel, and whose experience only shows up in the data.`,
    writtenCommunication: `"A PM who writes well, thinks well. The document is the proof." WHAT THIS IS Almost everything consequential in product management happens through documents. Your documents are your most visible work — what people share when you are not in the room. The most important shift: think of a document not as a final answer but as a thinking tool. You write to figure things out, then share to get the holes in your thinking identified before you build the wrong thing.`,
    productStorytelling: `"A strategy that cannot be told is a strategy that cannot be executed."  This produces accurate, trusted information. The gap is narrative — the ability to make an argument that people remember, repeat, and act on without being in the room. Operational communication answers 'what happened.' Product storytelling answers 'why it matters and where we are going.' THE BIG IDEA Storytelling for a PM is Distribution Leverage.`,
    stakeholderInfluence: `"Do not blame the person. Fix the system they are operating in." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You have built real influence through execution credibility. People trust you because you deliver. You know how to get things done through relationships, how to navigate organisational dynamics, and how to make a request land well. This is genuine influence, not just authority. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in the direction of influence. Operators influence toward delivery outcomes: get the team to hit the deadline, get the stakeholder to unblock the dependency, get the resource approved.`,
  },
  advocate: {
    productSense: `"Product sense is noticing what everyone else walks past." WHAT THIS IS Product sense is the ability to look at a product and know, without being told, what is right and what is off. It is taste applied to products. Advocates often have strong product sense for the user experience layer — you notice bad error messages, poor empty states, confusing flows. The PM extension is expanding that taste to cover strategic fit, metric alignment, and build sequencing. KEY FRAMEWORK — THE INTELLIGENT BET MAKER Every product decision is a bet.`,
    guesstimates: `"You do not need the exact answer. You need a good enough answer fast enough to make a decision."  'I need more data' is the Advocate's instinctive response. The PM instinct is different: 'What do I know right now that lets me make a defensible approximation?' Guesstimates are not about precision. They are about structured thinking under uncertainty — which is something you do every day when you research users.`,
    prioritisation: `"Every yes is a hundred nos. Make the nos on purpose."  This is not wrong — user pain is a valid signal. But it is incomplete. Prioritisation requires balancing user pain against business impact, engineering effort, and strategic fit. The mistake is treating emotional weight as equivalent to impact weight. A PM must make the trade-offs explicit, not intuitive.`,
    productStrategy: `"Strategy is not what you will do. It is what you will not do." ' User pain is the input to strategy, not the strategy itself. The mistake is treating a compelling user story as a strategic argument. Stakeholders who hear 'users are frustrated' need to hear 'here is the bet we are making and why this sequence of investment produces the best outcome for users and the business.`,
    competitiveAnalysis: `"Do not just map what competitors do. Map where they choose not to compete." WHAT THIS IS Competitive analysis is understanding your market — who else is solving the same problem, how, for whom, and where the gaps are. The most common version is a feature comparison matrix. The more valuable version asks: where are all the players choosing not to compete, and why? The empty space is almost always more valuable than the crowded space. KEY FRAMEWORK — FEATURE MATRIX WITH STRATEGIC TAGS Layer 1 — Feature Matrix Map each competitor's core capabilities against the user needs they address.`,
    metricsKpis: `"Numbers without context are just noise. Numbers with context are a superpower." ' These answers are right about what matters. They are wrong about how to measure it. Every qualitative user goal has a quantitative proxy — finding that proxy is the skill. THE BIG IDEA Metrics are the product's vital signs.`,
    abTesting: `"The only way to know if something works is to test it on real people doing real things."  This instinct is right for discovery. It is insufficient for validation. The limitation of qualitative research is that it cannot tell you which of two solutions is better. A/B testing is how you answer that question at scale without asking users what they prefer — because users are terrible at predicting their own behaviour.`,
    goToMarket: `"A great product with the wrong GTM is a tree falling in an empty forest." WHAT THIS IS Go-to-Market is the complete system for how your product reaches the people it is meant for — how they discover it, buy it, start using it, and tell others. GTM failure is almost always a mismatch: the way you are trying to sell the product does not match what you are selling. A product requiring a 45-minute onboarding call cannot be sold through a Facebook ad. A ₹50,000 enterprise subscription cannot be sold through self-serve sign-up.`,
    roadmapping: `"A roadmap is not a promise. It is a statement of priorities." WHAT THIS IS A roadmap connects what you are doing today to what you are trying to become. It is a communication tool as much as a planning tool. Its most underappreciated function: it is a political shield. Once agreed upon and visible, a PM can decline ad-hoc requests by pointing to it — 'that is not in our current strategic themes.' The no is structural, not personal. KEY FRAMEWORK — VISION TO SPRINT • Vision: 20-year aspiration. Qualitative. • Mission: 3–5 year quantified target.`,
    stakeholderManagement: `"You are not the boss of anyone. You are the person everyone should want to work with." WHAT THIS IS PMs have enormous responsibility and almost no direct authority. Everything is done through influence, alignment, and trust. Stakeholder management is the practice of building those things deliberately. The most common failure: PMs who walk into stakeholder conversations with the answer already decided and use the conversation to sell rather than to listen. People can feel when they are being sold to rather than consulted.`,
    techFundamentals: `"You do not need to write code. You need to understand what the code is doing and why it matters."  They disengage when the conversation turns to APIs, databases, or infrastructure, and defer entirely to engineering. This erodes trust. Engineering teams respect PMs who can engage with technical trade-offs, ask the right question about a system constraint, and understand why a feature is harder than it sounds. You do not need to write code.`,
    aiMlForPms: `"AI is not a feature. It is a capability layer that changes what problems you can solve."  The gap is not asking the upstream questions first: what kind of AI system is this, what are its structural failure modes, and which product decisions are impossible to make without understanding the probabilistic nature of the model underneath. AI fluency for PMs starts with the mechanics, not the interface.`,
    dataSql: `"Data tells you what happened. Judgment tells you what to do about it."  They are less comfortable with quantitative data. The gap shows up when a stakeholder asks 'show me the data' and the Advocate can describe what users said but cannot pull the table that shows what users did. You do not need to become a data analyst.`,
    systemDesign: `"System design is the craft of identifying bottlenecks before users do."  They participate in system design conversations by describing what users need and then deferring completely on how it gets built. The gap: system design decisions directly constrain product decisions. A data model choice made in sprint one can make a feature impossible in sprint forty. PMs who understand system design protect future optionality. PMs who do not become prisoners of their own architecture.`,
    userResearch: `"Your job is not to validate what you already believe. Your job is to be surprised." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You know how to run interviews. You understand the difference between a leading question and an open question. You have built empathy maps, journey maps, and personas. You know how to recruit users, run sessions, and synthesise patterns from qualitative data. You are probably better at this than most PMs you will work with. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is connecting your research to PM decisions. In a design role, research informs what to design.`,
    uxThinking: `"Great design is invisible. Bad design is all you can see." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You understand the UX iceberg: conceptual design at the foundation, information architecture and interaction design in the middle, visual design at the tip. You know that fixing the visual layer on top of a broken conceptual model is expensive cosmetic surgery on a structural problem. You have probably worked with the Design Sprint framework and understand how to prototype at the right level of fidelity.`,
    customerEmpathy: `"Empathy is not feeling bad for someone. It is understanding their world well enough to act on their behalf." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW Customer empathy is your deepest strength. You know the difference between sympathy (feeling bad for a user) and empathy (understanding their world well enough to anticipate what they need). You have run empathy mapping sessions. You know how to read the gap between what users say and what they do. You are probably the person in the room who notices when a product decision ignores the user's emotional state.`,
    writtenCommunication: `"A PM who writes well, thinks well. The document is the proof." WHAT THIS IS Almost everything consequential in product management happens through documents. Your documents are your most visible work — what people share when you are not in the room. The most important shift: think of a document not as a final answer but as a thinking tool. You write to figure things out, then share to get the holes in your thinking identified before you build the wrong thing.`,
    productStorytelling: `"A strategy that cannot be told is a strategy that cannot be executed." WHAT THIS IS Storytelling for a PM is Distribution Leverage — your ideas reach further than you physically can. A post you write, a decision you explain publicly, a product you ship and talk about adds to a library of proof that you think well. Advocates often have strong narrative instincts (from customer success, marketing, or design). The PM extension is making the business reasoning visible alongside the user story.`,
    stakeholderInfluence: `"Do not blame the person. Fix the system they are operating in." WHAT THIS IS Influence is not persuasion. It is building an environment where the right thing to do becomes the obvious thing to do. Stop thinking about people as obstacles and start thinking about the systems they are embedded in.`,
  },
  builder: {
    productSense: `"Product sense is noticing what everyone else walks past." WHAT THIS IS Product sense is the ability to look at a product — or a problem — and know, without being told, what is right and what is off. It is taste applied to products. Engineers have a version of this for code quality: you can look at a codebase and immediately know if it is well-structured. Product sense is the same instinct applied to user experience and strategic fit. KEY FRAMEWORK — THE INTELLIGENT BET MAKER Every product decision is a bet.`,
    guesstimates: `"You do not need the exact answer. You need a good enough answer fast enough to make a decision." WHAT THIS IS Guesstimates are structured estimation exercises. The point is not to produce the exact number. The point is to demonstrate clear thinking under uncertainty — to show that you can decompose a complex problem into logical components, make defensible assumptions, and arrive at a credible range. Engineers have a version of this in system design interviews: back-of-envelope capacity planning.`,
    prioritisation: `"Every yes is a hundred nos. Make the nos on purpose." WHAT THIS IS Prioritisation is the art of deciding what not to build. Engineers have a version of this in technical debt management — you cannot fix every bug, so you triage. PM prioritisation is the same skill applied to the roadmap: given everything we could do, what do we do first? KEY FRAMEWORKS ROI = Impact ÷ Effort For every idea: estimate impact (how many users affected, how frequently, how deeply) and effort (T-shirt size from engineering). Divide impact by effort. The ideas with the highest ratio go first.`,
    productStrategy: `"Strategy is not a roadmap. It is a set of deliberate bets about where to play and where not to play." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers optimise within the given constraints. They assume the problem is already correctly defined and focus on the best solution to it. The PM's job starts one level above: questioning whether the constraint is right, whether the problem is worth solving, and whether the direction serves a coherent long-term goal. The mistake is treating strategy as an input rather than something you own.`,
    competitiveAnalysis: `"Do not just map what competitors do. Map where they choose not to compete." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers approach competitive analysis like a spec comparison — feature by feature, column by column. This produces a checklist, not a strategy. The more valuable question is not 'which features do we have that they do not' — it is 'where are all the players choosing not to compete, and why?' The empty space in the market is almost always more valuable than the crowded space.`,
    metricsKpis: `"Numbers without context are just noise. Numbers with context are a superpower." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You know how to instrument code. You can set up event tracking, build dashboards, and run queries against an analytics backend. You understand the difference between server-side and client-side events. You have probably worked with tools like Mixpanel, Amplitude, or custom data pipelines. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is not technical — it is about which numbers matter and why. Engineers track what the system does. PMs track what users do, and connect those actions to business outcomes.`,
    abTesting: `"The only way to know if something works is to test it on real people doing real things." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You understand controlled experiments, statistical significance, and p-values. You have probably run feature flags, canary deployments, or split tests at the infrastructure level. You know the mechanics of variant assignment and the importance of sample isolation. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in how you frame what you are testing and why. Engineers test systems. PMs test hypotheses about user behaviour.`,
    goToMarket: `"A great product with the wrong GTM is a tree falling in an empty forest." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers treat distribution as an output — something that happens after the product is built. 'We will figure out marketing later' is the most common line. Later never comes, or comes too late. GTM is not the marketing team's job bolted on after launch. It is a design constraint that should influence what you build, at what price, for which segment, from day one. THE BIG IDEA Go-to-Market is the complete system for how your product reaches the people it is meant for.`,
    roadmapping: `"A roadmap is not a promise. It is a statement of priorities." WHAT THIS IS A roadmap is the document that connects what you are doing today to what you are trying to become. It is a communication tool as much as a planning tool — it tells every stakeholder, every engineer, and every new team member where you are going and what you are working on to get there. The most underappreciated function of a roadmap: it is a political shield. Once agreed upon and visible, a PM can decline an ad-hoc request by pointing to it — 'that is not in our current strategic themes.`,
    stakeholderManagement: `"You are not the boss of anyone. You are the person everyone should want to work with." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers manage stakeholders through clarity of spec — 'here is what we agreed to build.' This works inside the sprint. It fails at the product level, where stakeholders have different incentives, different time horizons, and different definitions of success. The PM must manage the system of relationships, not just the individual agreements. THE BIG IDEA PMs have enormous responsibility and almost no direct authority. You cannot order the engineering team to build something.`,
    techFundamentals: `"The PM who speaks engineering fluently earns trust that others have to borrow." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW This is your home territory. You understand system design, APIs, databases, caching, load balancing, and the trade-offs that go into architectural decisions. You can read and write code. You have shipped real systems. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is not knowledge — it is application. Tech fundamentals that live only in your head do not produce PM value. The translation layer is about deploying that knowledge at the right moments in the product conversation.`,
    aiMlForPms: `"AI is not a feature. It is a capability layer that changes what problems you can solve." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You understand how ML models work — training, inference, loss functions, overfitting. You have probably worked with model pipelines, feature stores, or MLOps infrastructure. You understand the difference between discriminative and generative models at a technical level. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in framing AI decisions as product decisions — for users and for the business — rather than engineering decisions. The questions change when you move from engineer to PM.`,
    dataSql: `"Data tells you what happened. Judgment tells you what to do about it." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW You can write SQL. You understand joins, aggregations, window functions, and query optimisation. You have probably worked with data warehouses, built dashboards, or designed schemas. Your data fluency is a genuine advantage in PM conversations. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in knowing which question to ask — not how to answer it. Engineers ask 'how do I compute this metric?' PMs ask 'is this the right metric to compute?' Leading vs.`,
    systemDesign: `"A PM who understands system design does not just approve the architecture. They shape the product constraints that make architecture decisions meaningful." WHAT YOU ALREADY KNOW System design is your strongest domain. You understand distributed systems, CAP theorem, consistency models, message queues, caching strategies, and the trade-offs between them. You have designed systems that scale. THE PM TRANSLATION LAYER The gap is in translating system constraints into product decisions — and product decisions back into system constraints.`,
    userResearch: `"Your job is not to validate what you already believe. Your job is to be surprised." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers do research to validate technical decisions: 'Is this architecture the right one?' The questions are closed-form and the answers are objective. User research is structurally different — the questions are open, the answers are messy, and the most important information is often what the user does not say directly. The mistake is bringing hypothesis-confirmation thinking to empathy-building work.`,
    uxThinking: `"Great design is invisible. Bad design is all you can see." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers understand UX as the visual layer — colours, fonts, polish. This is actually the least important layer. The most common engineer-turned-PM mistake is fixing the look of a product when the conceptual model underneath is broken. Users do not struggle with your app because the buttons are the wrong colour. They struggle because your app's mental model does not match how they think about the problem. THE BIG IDEA UX — User Experience — is everything a person feels while using your product.`,
    customerEmpathy: `"Empathy is not feeling bad for someone. It is understanding their world well enough to act on their behalf." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers develop deep empathy for the system they are building — they care about its elegance, its reliability, its performance. This is real craft. The missing layer is empathy for the person using the system: what they are afraid of, what they are embarrassed to admit, what they would love but would never think to ask for. Technical empathy and human empathy are different muscles.`,
    writtenCommunication: `"A PM who writes well, thinks well. The document is the proof." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers write documentation to describe what has been built. PM documents exist to decide what should be built — and why. The purpose is different. A spec that reads like documentation ('the system shall...') has already confused the two. PM writing is a thinking tool first and a communication tool second. If you do not understand the problem, your document will expose that immediately.`,
    productStorytelling: `"A strategy that cannot be told is a strategy that cannot be executed." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN Engineers present evidence. They show the data, walk through the analysis, and let the conclusion follow logically. This works for technical decisions among peers. It fails for building alignment across functions, for communicating with leadership, and for building a professional reputation in public. The missing piece is narrative — the ability to make an argument that people remember and repeat. THE BIG IDEA Think of how Amul gets milk to every corner of India.`,
    stakeholderInfluence: `"Do not blame the person. Fix the system they are operating in." THE ENGINEER MISTAKE PATTERN When a stakeholder keeps making the same 'irrational' request — adding scope, breaking prioritisation, overriding decisions — the engineer's instinct is to escalate or document the disagreement. The PM instinct is to ask: what in the system makes this request feel necessary to them? Changing a person is hard. Changing what makes their behaviour rational is leverage. THE BIG IDEA Influence is not persuasion. Persuasion is convincing someone to do what you want.`,
  },
}
